segments.text: Speaking of Bev Sheffield, I gained a good deal of respect for that man.
And I respected him very much as a professional.
He was in every sense a professional.
He was also a person who did something that I wish a lot of parks or recreation directors would do.
And I should not say parks, because William Osborne was head of parks.
division in the Public Works Department.
They have maintained a log to the very best of the ability of the department of every person who ever used City of Austin Park and Recreation facilities.
This was an amazing thing.
There were a couple of influences in this.
One was those neighborhood pools.
He kept a roster of the youngsters and the families they came from at all these neighborhood pools.
Because the pools would be open from about 6 or 6.30 in the morning.
They would shut down at 10 or 10.30, reopen at 2.30 or something like that in the afternoon, and be open until sunset.
Of course, the middle day thing was for cleaning and normal maintenance.
But it was also a way to be sure that the pools didn't just become a lounging place.
The mornings were particularly filled with swimming classes and various sorts of things.
But Bev used that as one group.
Secondly, the people who reserved tables in the municipal parks, he kept a permanent register of everybody
who requested, made a reservation of a picnic table or a camping spot, that is a day camp spot, in any city park.
He did the same thing for all of the people who used the municipal golf courses.
He maintained that.
Every tee-off time, he knew when every person had gone through.
He did the same thing for the tennis centers.
He kept a log of all of these people, and he made it a point.

And of course, at Zilker Park, if there were activities there, whoever the prime movers were of those activities, Bev Sheffield could call on these people who were active park users on any issue that might threaten the sanctity
or the utility, the protection of a park or a recreation program.
And I had occasion one time to be in his offices down along the river when there was some issue being proposed before the city council by some group.
And I don't remember what the issue was, but I remember Bev talking to his secretary
and saying, let's start a chain telephone call because the city council on whatever it was, Thursday morning or Tuesday morning, will have this issue up.
I know that these people will be interested.
At that city council meeting, which was in the old, then the city council chamber, which maybe could seat 100 people, he had over 200 people at the door.
And this was on less than a 24-hour notice.
Lots of pressure.
Lots of pressure, but pressure that wasn't misapplied.
It wasn't abused.
And Bev always knew exactly whether to use it or not use it.
And we were able, in the planning effort, to benefit from some of that.
The contrary was the...
Public Works Department had some rather narrow, in my judgment, narrow interpretations of what the thoroughfare system plan, major streets plan should be.
And they were very skittish about issues where proposals might require widening of right of way or something of this sort.
They would prefer, for example, to build four-lane thoroughfares with 36-foot of roadway.
Maybe 40 if they felt very generous.
This is a trademark of Austin, the narrow streets.
That's largely the Public Works Department influence.
Everybody that visits Austin remarks about this.
Part of that was almost a
A social philosophy, we don't want people to move too quickly.
The thoroughfare was seen as a route of convenience, not a route of necessity.
And therefore, that was a route to be preferred by people moving around the town, not to travel long distances, but just simply a route of travel, a route of convenience.
probably has done more through the years to limit what happened.
Hal had to work within the framework of getting, well, between two boundaries.
One was getting across the concepts of the thoroughfare plan, major streets plan.
The other was getting across or having to deal with public works people who, because they were engineering and the electrical engineer was the head of city government,
were very, very strong in their role and could almost effectively cancel out any planning effort that could be done.
So I think in the years subsequently, some of that control in public works, while it has diminished some, I don't see it really as having given way that much.
Gus Lavander, good sweep, was then head of Public Works Department.
Reuben Roundtree, that's R-O-U-N-T-R-E-A.
Lavander's L-E-V-A-N-D-E-R. Like lavender, but you reverse the A and the E. Gus was very pro-planning, but Reuben Roundtree was
very concerned about not infringing on neighboring property.
So if it came down to a question of widening right-of-way or having a narrower roadway, he would opt for the narrower roadway in preference to taking a row of houses or business furniture.
Hellwise, in later years when we were in Tulsa, I was confronted with the same problem with the director of public works in downtown Tulsa.
And he found out, apparently, because of previous experience in dealing with these folks, how to get around them.
And the city traffic engineer in Tulsa was due to retire in two years.

But in the meantime, he was blocking every proposal for a continuous, comprehensive, one-way street pattern throughout the center of downtown Tulsa, which was absolutely essential for getting it to work properly.
So Harold just simply hired Alan Voorhees to come in, and just simply by dint of professional overkill was able to convince the decision makers that that was the way to do it.
I think, by response, I think that where that can work in a city like Tulsa, could work in Dallas, could work in Fort Worth, I have to admit,
as much as I love the town, Austin is very, very, very provincial.
And the provincialism is one of the things that adds to its appeal and its attraction.
It's the thing that gets in its way a lot of times.
I don't know that even Alan Voorhees' organization could have overpowered that situation.
I really don't know that they could have because
The underlying philosophy was we don't want people to move quickly.
We want them to mosey along and enjoy the scenery.
So you don't need wide streets.
The same philosophy happens in Berkeley.
Oh, is that right?
Yeah.
And there have been more than one comparisons drawn between Berkeley and Austin.
And the philosophy in Berkeley is that it's a city of neighborhoods, and that people who are driving in Berkeley
in Berkeley because they want to be there.
They don't go through Berkeley to get somewhere else.
Yeah, I've heard that.
Looking at it a little further, looking at the consequences of the plan that Hal developed, I would also say that the conditions in Austin have also changed, as they have everywhere, but perhaps

because Austin is now deciding it should be reaching out to the outside world, that the Balcones Research Lab operations, the whole concept of the computer technology and all of the offerings there, that seems to be influencing Austin, even to the extent
that we will see in the Times Herald in Dallas.

In the want ads, City of Austin, that's all it will say, City of Austin under a heading, won't even advertise for a specific job, but they will have periodically these one-liners in the classifieds, obviously trying to keep people in the Dallas area interested in what's going on in city government in Austin.
Nobody else is putting those ads in except the city.
People in College Station don't read the Dallas Times-Herald.
Oh, they don't?
That's interesting.
They do good to read.
Because of the comments of your sports editors about our recruiting methods.
That needn't be on the page.

Beyond the plan for the city, the long-term plan that Hal Wise and his associates developed, and while I say developed, it was really in concert with input from the staff, which were essentially concerned with the day-to-day planning activities, and input from department heads.
I think there are a couple of things that should be noted.
Were there staff planners that should be mentioned?
Yeah.
OK. Let me just mention that.
One of the people that was a very strong personality in all of this on the day-to-day operations was Wayne Golden.
Wayne was in a rather lesser level position when I went there as planning director.
By the time I left, he was heading up the current planning activities.

Then by the time the major effort of Hal Wise was completed, Evelyn Slatum Butler was ready to, she was moving into a number two position under Hoyle Osborne, who was then responsible for advanced planning.
in between Jerry Finley who came down from the state of Washington and no I take that back he was from Oregon and he was essentially our staff research person Ruben Vallejo
who has since been with HUD over the years, based in Fort Worth, and was, in fact, planner on the staff in Fort Worth when I went there later, many years later, and then left and went with HUD.
These were some of the key people in the staff.
There were some others in various roles, but I'd like to point out a couple of things.
One is, because of Wayne Golden's
efforts.
And this was the frontline soldier kind of effort that had to be dealt with, had to be worked at all the time.
Wayne, through the supportive provision in the Austin City Charter and the supporting provisions in state law providing for extraterritorial jurisdiction,

Wayne was able to convince the county commissioners that we should not be giving final clearance to subdivision plants outside the city limits within our extraterritorial jurisdiction unless the county commissioners were also willing to impose certain standards in the nature of public improvements on streets and
and other public facilities.
The city of Austin had leverage in this because there were, I believe at the time in existence then, seven water control improvement districts that extended outside the city limits.
In fact, went all the way to the county line.
And in some cases, north and south went beyond the county line.
So that in one area of the north, for instance, one of those water control improvement districts, as I recall, was into Williamson County.

That meant, because the city of Austin was the supplier of the water, of the treated water, to the water control improvement district, the city of Austin could impose certain restrictions or improvement requirements
on any subdivision in this extraterritorial jurisdiction, even if it were 10, 15 miles outside the city limits.
But that would be fine with respect to utilities.
But what we did not have adequate support on was the boundary streets.
Nor did we really have a level of authority
within the subdivisions as to street improvements.

And in that regard, Wayne Golden made it a point to convince the county commissioners, and he deserves full credit for it, that they should adopt some standards for street construction in unincorporated areas.
Now, the standards were not that great.
As one would look back on it today, one would probably say,
hey, why didn't he do something more than that?
The truth of the matter was, up until that point, we had no standards.
And it was a matter of getting something on the books where there would be a good, reasonably durable, 20-year life hard top road.
And Wayne was the person who really managed to put that together, that idea.

And the county commissioners backed it, and they would not approve the subdivision outside the city limits, nor the providing of any county services to that subdivision until the developer put those streets in.
Now, we didn't have the lever to get them to maintain the streets.
But the county then, once the street would be dedicated, then had to pick up the maintenance responsibility.
County commissioners were beginning to see the consequence of poor streets.
So Wayne really deserves credit for that.
The other thing that we were able to accomplish was a base mapping program, which for the most part was my brainchild.
And we were able to get through tax maps and other maps from public works departments

We were able to get the material using US Geological Survey photos as the controls and maps that USGS made for us, base maps with the appropriate property identification for a very, very large area in Austin and Travis County.
I don't know whether those maps are still being used.
I suspect not.
Certainly today there are more adequate methods of putting things together.
But we had one whole wall that was 8 feet high and 12 feet long where the maps were literally fitted together like pieces of a jigsaw puzzle.
And then from that shot down so that we could get base maps.
a tremendous undertaking, but it did turn out to be, I think, a very worthwhile endeavor.
Now, Austin has always had a particularly good reputation in terms of subdivision review procedures within the planning department.
Would you like to go into that?
That procedure, basically,
After I arrived in Austin in 53, we built on the procedure, expanded on it from what had been used up until that point, and Wayne Golden was the man responsible for maintaining that procedure.
He and a man by the name of Foxworth were both involved in this to some extent.

The thing that happened with the establishment of the Planning Commission under the new city charter was to make clear the responsibility of the Planning Commission to exercise per state law, but in behalf of all city departments, the review and approval of subdivision plans, both the preliminary plans and the final plans for record.
The commission,
set up a schedule.
And this was perhaps somewhat unique, especially at that time it was unique.
And that was that the commission set its regular meetings every third week.
Those were, it did not matter what the month was.
We started in the first week of the year, and every third week thereafter, there was a Planning Commission meeting.
The Board of Adjustment,
met also on a three-week schedule in between those.
But the commission's two, or I should, well, three committees, a master plan committee, a subdivision committee, and a zoning committee met on three-week schedules also.
The zoning committee meeting two weeks, as I recall, two weeks before the commission meeting.
subdivision review committee or plaque committee meeting one week before the commission meeting.
One of the things that was accomplished there, and I think it is really a credit to the whole Austin staff, was a desire to see an improved quality of subdivisions.
And subdivision control was viewed as being rather critical.
Zoning was, I hate to say it, but
seemed to be flaunted some, and I guess to some extent that accusation might still be made in lots of cities, in that it was a political trade-off or something or other.
Not a payoff, but a trade-off.
If you allow this, then what happens here on this other property?
But with subdivision control, there was an earnest desire to improve the
the conveyance of property to be sure that the necessary provisions be made for public utilities and private utilities and for protection of drainage ways.
There was a concern within the planning department about adequacy and right of way for especially the major streets.
But the whole process went very, very smoothly.

And I think even people with whom I had dealings, sometimes at moments of some heightened difference of opinion, had to say that they felt they were basically and overall treated fairly, even though they might not like the decision that came out of a subdivision committee meeting or out of the commission meeting on a proposed plan.
For the most part, I think they had to say the process worked well and nobody was handicapped.
Nobody was hindered unnecessarily in accomplishing what they wanted to do.
One of those is a builder, a developer, that is still building right here in the Dallas area, and that's Nash Phillips Copas.
Nash Phillips was always the arbitrator in the organization.
Clyde Copas was sort of like the baddie rooster, always wanting to
get on with something and not pay too much attention or wanting to be bothered too much by rules and regulations.
But that's when Clyde was younger.
And I think he's changed his line some since over the years.
But you mentioned Evelyn.
Yes.
What was her role?
Evelyn had the review in the case of subdivisions and of zoning.
She had the review from the standpoint of,
The plan, the long-range plan, what were the implications for the long-range plan?
And where Wayne was really the administrator for subdivisions, Evelyn was the reviewer, not on the internals of the subdivision, but rather on the impact issue.
What externally could impact on the subdivision, and how would the subdivision itself impact on the community?
So hers was really one of looking at the long range consequences more than the short range.
Wade's was the job of getting this thing through the process and through the pipeline.
Hoyle, Osborne, had responsibility in examining subdivisions to the extent, as I recall, to the extent that he would try to
make some judgments on either the social or the economic consequences of a particular subdivision on a total area related to things that Evelyn was looking at.
But she was normally looking at the physical design implications.
He was looking more at the social and economic implications.
And team-wise, it was a pretty darn good team, frankly.
I always felt very good about that situation.
Then you left to go to... Yeah, when I left Austin, I went to Yuma, Arizona.
What year was that?
That was 1958.
I was in Austin from 53 to 58.
And Hoyle Osborne took over.
And Hoyle then took over immediately.
I left the operation in his good hands.
And I might add, there was one other person there that was not a planner, but had been in the operation before that,
And that was Jewel Osburn.
She's since retired from the city.
And she was... Any relation?
No, no relation, and the spelling is different.
Hers without an E on the end of it.
O-S-B-O-R-N and his O-S-B-O-R-N-E. And then there was a William Osburn in public works who was O-S-B-U-R-N.
But Jewel Osburn was...

secretary under Bill Parker, William O. Parker, when Bill was, and he was really my predecessor, but he had been in the job on somewhat of a staff support role under Public Works before the charter revisions.
He was in part of that time, during part of those several years before, he was finishing up his degree in architecture.
at UT Austin.
And he had also done, in fact, he was the designer.
This is somewhat interesting because the city of Austin and Walter Seaholm, the city manager, really wouldn't give Bill Parker the freedom to move like a planning operation should have.
But Bill was the designer for Mo Ranch, which is the Presbyterian facility that
down in Kerrville area that is even to this day very popular amongst people in the Presbyterian Church that go down there for retreats and so on.
And he was really the planner for that facility, and it's been built largely according to the design concepts that Bill Parker laid out.
But Bill would have been great there if he'd had the kind of freedom I had, but he just didn't have it.
He was the first planning director.
He was called City Planner.
That was his official title.
And never recognized in the status of a department head.
I was the first one going in with recognition as a department head.
When I left Austin in 1958, I went to Yuma to head the city county planning department.
And in that particular instance, they had a plan done by Stanford Research Institute, which was questionable in a lot of areas.
I had to live with the thing.
I didn't know that they did plan.
I think it was one of the few ventures.

And the person who had preceded me who was there before SRI came in was an electro-hydraulics engineer who somehow or other had happened in the Yuma because of being associated with dams and hydro-generating facilities.
in the Northwest and the Colorado River and so on.
He wound up there.
My principal activities in Yuma were one, to bridge conflicts between city and county government.
Second, it was obviously not possible to do much since the community was on the plan, since the community was very proud of having that plan in their hands.
Although there was a lot of
negative feeling toward my predecessor.
I had pretty good support from both city and county government.
In fact, I would say overall very good support from the county supervisors.
The city government, which was under a mayor council operational form, was not too well oriented to planning because
All of their decisions were very much short range this year or next year at the most.
And many of the things that really needed to be addressed were the long range issues.
However, a couple of things were accomplished in very specific terms.
One was getting some
coordination with the State Highway Department on the location of the Interstate Highway coming out of Tucson and Phoenix.
